#| "The kernel often does allocations of memory that are needed for only the "
#| "duration of a single system call. In a user process, such short-term "
#| "memory would be allocated on the run-time stack. Because the kernel has a "
#| "limited run-time stack, it is not feasible to allocate even moderate-"
#| "sized blocks of memory on it. Consequently, such memory must be allocated "
#| "through a more dynamic mechanism. For example, when the system must "
#| "translate a pathname, it must allocate a 1-Kbyte buffer to hold the name. "
#| "Other blocks of memory must be more persistent than a single system call, "
#| "and thus could not be allocated on the stack even if there was space. An "
#| "example is protocol-control blocks that remain throughout the duration of "
